                android:text="Clean and Prepare Mussels:

Scrub the mussels under running water and remove the beards. Discard any mussels with cracked shells or those that do not close when tapped.
Sauté Aromatics:

In a pot, heat cooking oil over medium heat. Sauté the minced garlic, sliced ginger, and sliced onions until fragrant.
Add Mussels:

Add the cleaned mussels to the pot. Stir to combine with the aromatics.
Pour Water or Broth:

Pour in the water or fish broth. Bring it to a boil and let it simmer until the mussels open. Discard any mussels that do not open.
Add Papaya:

Add the sliced green papaya to the pot. Simmer until the papaya is tender.
Season:

Season the soup with fish sauce or salt to taste. Add ground black pepper for additional flavor.
Add Malunggay Leaves:

Once the papaya is tender, add the malunggay leaves to the pot. Cook for a few more minutes until the malunggay leaves are wilted.
Optional: Add Green Chili Peppers:

If you prefer a bit of heat, add green chili peppers to the pot. Adjust the quantity according to your spice preference.
Serve:

Serve the Tinolang Tahong hot with steamed rice.
Accompany the dish with calamansi or lemon wedges for a burst of citrus flavor."
